---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const layerExample = `@layer legacy, settings, base, utilities,
layout, components, theme, hacks;`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Layers"
    description="Understanding cascade layers in Layered Semantic CSS, including legacy and hacks layers."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Layers</p>

        <h1>
            Layer architecture
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            LSCSS uses explicit cascade layers to create predictable override
            behaviour, reduce specificity problems, and stop CSS from turning
            into a knife fight.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Layer sections">
        <a href="#layer-order">Layer order</a>
        <a href="#legacy-layer">Legacy</a>
        <a href="#hacks-layer">Hacks</a>
        <a href="#why-it-matters">Why it matters</a>
    </nav>

    <section class="content-block">
        <CodeExample code={layerExample} />
    </section>

    <section id="layer-order" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Layer order matters
        </h2>

        <p>
            Layer order controls precedence. Source order inside a layer matters
            less than the layer structure itself. Lower layers lose to higher
            layers, even if they appear later in the source.
        </p>

        <p>
            This allows architecture to control overrides instead of relying on
            selector weight and repeated specificity escalation.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="legacy-layer" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Why the legacy layer exists
        </h2>

        <p>
            The <code>legacy</code> layer exists so older project CSS and
            third-party styles can be imported first at the lowest priority.
            This means your structured layers immediately become more important
            without needing heavier selectors or override battles.
        </p>

        <p>
            Legacy CSS should not be allowed to define the architecture of a new
            system. It should be contained low in the cascade and gradually
            replaced over time.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="hacks-layer" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Why the hacks layer exists
        </h2>

        <p>
            The <code>hacks</code> layer is a controlled place for temporary,
            urgent fixes. Sometimes production needs a fast correction before a
            full refactor is realistic.
        </p>

        <p>
            Hacks should be visible, isolated, and treated like technical debt,
            not hidden inside normal component CSS where they quietly become
            permanent.
        </p>

        <p>
            A hack should be moved, rewritten, or removed as soon as possible.
            The hacks layer is a quarantine zone, not a retirement home.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="why-it-matters" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Why this matters
        </h2>

        <p>
            Legacy and hacks layers stop teams from solving every problem with
            stronger selectors, more <code>!important</code>, and quiet regret.
            They make technical debt visible and keep the rest of the system
            cleaner.
        </p>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
